## Analysis

> #### Hypothesis

---

```{r}
# 1) How many seniors did not share their `favourite physical activity`?
n_na = sum(is.na(HSS$Favourite_physical_activity))
n_non_na = sum(!is.na(HSS$Favourite_physical_activity))

n_seniors <- n_na + n_non_na

 
# 2) How many seniors are in either activity group?
counts <- HSS2 %>%
  count(activity_group)

group1 <- counts$n[counts$activity_group == "Structured"]
group2 <- counts$n[counts$activity_group == "Recreational"]
```

From the survey, `r n_non_na`/`r n_seniors` seniors shared their favorite physical activity. Of those who did respond `r group1` prefer structures activities whereas `r group2` prefer recreational activities. The question we're asking is does activity type preference impact the mean time taken on the memory challenge administered to the seniors or are the means the same for both groups indicating activity type preference has a very weak impact if any at all.

We'll state our hypotheses as,

$$
\\H_0: \ \mu_{Recreational} - \mu_{Structured} = 0
\\H_a: \ \mu_{Recreational} - \mu_{Structured} \neq 0
\\ \alpha = 0.1 \ \text{(10% CI)}
\\ \ 
\\ \text{Or, stated more simply:}
\\ \
\\H_0: \ \mu_{Recreational} = \mu_{Structured}
\\H_a: \ \mu_{Recreational} \neq \mu_{Structured}
\\ \alpha = 0.1 \ \text{(10% CI)}
$$

</BR>





